The paper deals with game-theoretic routing problems, which are typically studied in the subfield of computer science known as game theory (cs.GT). The use of bandwidth allocation and capacity constraints suggests a focus on networking and communication (cs.NI), while the consideration of time-dependent allocation rates suggests a possible connection to information theory (cs.IT). The study of equilibria and algorithms for these games may also fall under the subfields of social choice theory (cs.SI) and distributed computing (cs.DC).
